{{Infobox film | name = Minerita | image = | image_size = | caption = | director = Raúl de la Fuente | producer = Amaia Remirez | writer = Raúl de la Fuente | starring = | music = Mikel Salas | cinematography = | editing = | studio = Kanaki Films | distributor = | released = {{Film date|2015|04|17|Tribeca Film Festival}} | runtime = 28 minutes | country = Spain/Bolivia | language = Spanish }}
'''''Minerita''''' is a 2015 Spanish short-[[documentary film]] about three women working the [[Cerro de Potosí|Potosi mines]] in Bolivia. The documentary was well received by critics and earned widespread critical acclaim. ''Minerita'' was shortlisted with nine other documentaries from 74 entries submitted to the [[88th Academy Awards]] in the [[Academy Award for Best Documentary (Short Subject)|Documentary Short Subject]] category,<ref>{{cite web|title=10 DOC SHORTS ON OSCAR’S 2015 SHORTLIST|url=https://www.oscars.org/news/10-doc-shorts-oscars-2015-shortlist|publisher=[[Oscars.org]]|date=October 26, 2015|accessdate=October 28, 2015}}</ref> but was not nominated as a finalist.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://oscar.go.com/nominees/documentary-short |title=Documentary (Short Subject) – Oscar Nominees 2016 |date=January 14, 2016 |accessdate=February 1, 2016}}</ref>
==Plot== ''Minerita'' is the story of three women—Lucía (40), Ivone (16) and Abigail (17), who work as night watch women in the [[Cerro Rico]] mining district in [[Potosi, Bolivia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=International Documentary Film Festival Amsterdam - Minerita |url=https://www.idfa.nl/industry/tags/project.aspx?id=824faffb-7e51-4e26-b94c-9f3556a9cea5|publisher=International Documentary Film Festival|accessdate=October 31, 2015}}</ref>
==Awards== * Social Impact Media Awards - Best Short Documentary Director.{{cn|date=July 2016}} * [[28th Goya Awards]] - Best Documentary Short Film.{{cn|date=July 2016}}
==See also== *''[[The Devil's Miner]]'', a documentary film about child miners of the [[Cerro Rico]].
